{
  "doc_id": "9107",
  "text": "Currently, power allocation problems for OFDM-based CRNs have been studied from different optimization objectives and mathematical tools. In [CITATION_1] , a subcarrier power allocation scheme via water-filling formula was proposed to maximize the sum capacity of SU subject to the constraints of total power, each subcarrier power and the aggregate interference power of PU. The authors address the single-user scenario. In [CITATION_2] , for an OFDM CRN with single-PU-multi-SU scenario, a hierarchic power allocation algorithm based on Stackelberg game theory was designed subject to the total power constraint of SU and the interference-to-signal ratio (ISR) constraint. In [CITATION_3] , the authors studied the subcarrier allocation and power allocation problem for an OFDM-based CRN where an opportunistic power allocation method was proposed to achieve the capacity maximization of SU by using Lagrange method. In addition, the outage probability of PU was analyzed to keep it within a tolerable range. In [CITATION_4] , the authors jointly considered the power and subcarrier optimization problem for a multiuser OFDM-based CRN. A dynamic resource allocation algorithm was proposed under the QoS constraint of PU and the proportional constraint of SU. All above aforementioned works consider power allocation problem under the assumption of perfect channel information. For example, SUs can exactly obtain the channel gains between SUs and PUs, channel gain among SUs and interference channel gains from PUs. However, in practical CRNs, these parameters can not be perfectly obtained due to the stochastic nature of wireless channel and delays. The effectiveness of the designed algorithms (e.g., [CITATION_5] - [CITATION_6] ) may be degraded when the channel uncertainties and interference uncertainties are not taken into account.",
